definition.value: The conjugate base of gamma-amino-beta-hydroxybutyric acid arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A  ribose diphosphate carrying an additional phosphate group at position 5.

Any member of a group of fat-soluble retinoids produced via metabolism of provitamin A carotenoids that exhibit biological activity against vitamin A deficiency. Vitamin A is involved in immune function, vision, reproduction, and cellular communication.
An antagonist that interferes with the action of the calcium-binding messenger protein calmodulin.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of guanidinoacetic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A pyridinium ion obtained by protonation of the ring nitrogen of pyridoxal.
A pyridinium ion obtained by protonation of both nitrogens of pyridoxamine.
Any steroid substituted by a formyl group.
Any bacterial metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in Mycoplasma genitalium.
A carboxylic acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of a dicarboxylic acid monoester.

An echinocandin initially isolated as a very minor bioactive fermentation product of Glarea lozoyensis (originally known as Zalerion arboricola). Subsequent random mutagenesis work and optimisation of the fermentation medium permitted the industrial production of pneumocandin B0, which is used as the starting point for the synthesis of the antifungal drug caspofungin.
A steroid compound with a structure based on a 27-carbon (cholestane) skeleton.
A steroid compound with a structure based on a 24-carbon (cholane) skeleton.
A steroid compound with a structure based on a 19-carbon (androstane) skeleton.
Any steroid (or derivative) based on a cholane skeleton.
A DNA polymerase inhibitor that interferes with the action of a DNA-directed DNA polymerase (EC 2.7.7.7).
Any steroid (or derivative) based on a stigmastane skeleton.
Any sterol based on a stigmastane skeleton.
An icosanoid anion arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function of any hydroxyicosatetraenoic acid.
An icosanoid anion arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function of any oxoicosatetraenoic acid.
An unsaturated fatty acid anion obtained by the deprotonation of the carboxy group of any octadecanoid.
An unsaturated fatty acid anion obtained by the deprotonation of the carboxy group of any hydroxyoctadecadienoic acid.
An octadecanoid anion anion obtained by the deprotonation of the carboxy group of any hydroperoxyoctadecadienoic acid.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid anion carrying one or more hydroxy substituents.
Any steroid acid anion based on a cholanic acid skeleton.
A class of carbonyl compound encompassing dicarboxylic acids and any derivatives obtained by substitution of either one or both of the carboxy hydrogens.
A molecular entity that can undergo reduction by the gain of hydrogen atom(s).
A sphingomyelin d18:1 obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of pentacosanoic acid with the amino group of sphingosine.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the sphingoid base and fatty acyl groups is 43 with 1 double bond.
Any member of the class of benzoquinones that is 1,4-benzoquinone or its C-substituted derivatives.
Any quinone in which one or more of the carbons making up the quinone moiety is substituted by a hydroxy group.
A naphthoquinone in which the oxo groups of the quinone moiety are at positions 1 and 4 of the parent naphthalene ring.
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of hyaluronic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
Any naphthoquinone in which the naphthaoquinone moiety is substituted by at least one hydroxy group.
Any member of the class of 1,4-naphthoquinones in which the naphthoquinone moiety is substituted by at least one hydroxy group.
A retinoid derived from 3,4-desaturation of the beta-ionone ring of all-trans-retinol.
A citrate anion obtained by deprotonation of the three carboxy groups as well as the hydroxy group of citric acid.
Any aromatic amide obtained by acylation of aniline.
Any trienoic fatty acid containing 16 carbons.
Any trienoic fatty acid containing 18 carbons.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid containing 18 carbons and 4 double bonds.
Any monounsaturated fatty acid containing 20 carbons and 1 double bond.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid containing 20 carbons and 4 double bonds.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid containing 20 carbons and 5 double bonds.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid containing 22 carbons and 4 double bonds.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid containing 22 carbons and 5 double bonds.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid containing 22 carbons and 6 double bonds.
